      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <p class="lead">Senior night is the most emotional event of the season. Whether it's a pre-game ceremony or part of the end-of-year banquet, the night belongs to the seniors and their families. Here's a complete script and planning guide to get it right.</p>

        <h2>The Ceremony Flow (30 Minutes)</h2>
        <table>
          <tr>
            <th>Segment</th>
            <th>Time</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Welcome & introduction</td>
            <td>2 min</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Senior walk-in (one by one)</td>
            <td>2 min per senior</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Coach's remarks per senior</td>
            <td>1 min per senior</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Parent/guardian recognition</td>
            <td>30 sec per senior</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Senior gift presentation</td>
            <td>1 min total</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Closing & team photo</td>
            <td>5 min</td>
          </tr>
        </table>

        <h2>Announcer Script Template</h2>

        <h3>Opening</h3>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"Good [evening/afternoon] everyone. Thank you for being here to celebrate our senior [sport] athletes and their families.</p>
          <p>This night is about honoring the commitment, work, and passion these seniors have brought to our program over the last four years. Each of them has left their mark on this team."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h3>Senior Walk-In Format</h3>
        <p>As each senior is announced (preferably alphabetically), they walk across a stage or through a tunnel of teammates:</p>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"Our first senior is [name], number [jersey]. [Name] has been a [position] for [years on team] years. [Quick highlight: a big game, a leadership role, a notable moment]. After high school, [name] plans to [college/military/work]. Let's show our appreciation!"</p>
        </blockquote>

        <p>After the walk-in, the senior's parent or guardian stands and is acknowledged.</p>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"Joining [name] tonight are [parent/guardian names]. Thank you for sharing your athlete with us and for all the support over the years."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h3>Coach's Personal Remarks</h3>
        <p>After the announcer reads the bio, the coach adds a personal 30-60 second memory for each senior. This is the most meaningful part of the night.</p>
        <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Write these ahead of time. Even two sentences per athlete makes a huge impact. "I'll never forget when [name] dove for that ball in the fifth set against [rival school]. That's the kind of effort that defined their time here."</p>

        <h2>Senior Gift Ideas</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Custom centerpiece keepsake</strong> — A 3D printed sport centerpiece with the senior's name and number. Sits on the banquet table during the season and becomes a permanent memento.</li>
          <li><strong>Photo frame with team photo</strong> — Frame includes the team photo and a spot for their individual senior photo.</li>
          <li><strong>Letter from coach</strong> — Handwritten letter. Takes 10 minutes per athlete and means more than any store-bought gift.</li>
          <li><strong>Team signed ball or jersey</strong> — Each teammate signs it with a personal message.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What Parents Want</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>A photo of their athlete</strong> — Make sure a photographer is capturing each senior during their walk-in</li>
          <li><strong>Time to take photos after</strong> — Build in 10-15 minutes after the ceremony for family photos</li>
          <li><strong>Clear communication</strong> — Send parents the schedule a week in advance so grandparents, aunts, and uncles can coordinate</li>
        </ul>

